ardinia, Italy","Arborea, Oristan, Sardegna, Italy":"Arborea, Oristano, Sardinia, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pelegrina","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: from the female personal name <i>Peregrina</i>, or a nickname from the feminine form of <i>peregrino</i> ‘pilgrim’ (see   Peregrino  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Peregrino","meanings":["From Latin <i>Peregrinus</i> ‘foreigner, stranger’, a name borne by various early Christian saints, perhaps referring to the belief that men and women are merely sojourners upon the earth, their true home being in heaven. In modern times the name is rare, borne mostly by Roman Catholics, who choose it in honour of those saints."]}]},{"name":"di","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Diana   and   Diane ."],"variants":[{"name":"Diana","meanings":["Name borne in Roman mythology by the goddess of the moon and of hunting, equivalent to the Greek Artemis. In mythology she is characterized as both beautiful and chaste. Her name is of ancient and uncertain derivation. It probably contains a first element that is also found in the name of the Greek god <i>Dionysos</i> (  see  Dennis  ) and the Latin name of the supreme god <i>Jupiter</i>. It was adopted in Britain during the Tudor period as a learned name, a borrowing from Latin influenced by the French form   Diane .  Although it was much used by Elizabethan poets celebrating the virgin goddess and alluding to the Virgin Queen, it was not particularly popular as a given name until the end of the 19th century. In earlier centuries some clergymen were reluctant to baptize girls with this pagan name, mindful of the riots against St Paul stirred up by worshippers of Diana of the Ephesians (Acts 19:24–41). In the late 20th century, its popularity received a boost because of its association with the late  Diana , Princess of Wales (  1961–97 ), who was renowned for her beauty, glamour, and compassion."]},{"name":"Diane","meanings":["form of   Diana  , now also widely used in the English-speaking world. It was especially popular among the Renaissance aristocracy, who loved hunting and were therefore proud to name their daughters after the classical goddess of the chase."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Pelegrina di Arborea was born about 1128, in Arborea, Oristano, Sardinia, Italy. She had at least 1 daughter with Barison I de Lacon Serra."},"et":{"about 1128–":"umbes 1128–Surnud","1124–Male":"1124–Surnud","1150–1204":"1150–1204","1128–Female":"1128–Surnud","1128":"1128","1204":"1204","1124":"1124","about 1128":"umbes 1128","1150":"1150","Laconi,Oristano,Sardinia,Italy.":"Laconi, Oristano, Sardegna, Itaalia","Arborea, Oristan, Sardegna, Italy":"Arborea, Oristano, Sardegna, Itaalia"},"fi":{"about 1128–":"noin 1128–Kuollut","1124–Male":"1124–Kuollut","1150–1204":"1150–1204","1128–Female":"1128–Kuollut","1128":"1128","1204":"1204","1124":"1124","about 1128":"noin 1128","1150":"1150","Laconi,Oristano,Sardinia,Italy.":"Laconi, Oristano, Sardegna, Italia","Arborea, Oristan, Sardegna, Italy":"Arborea, Oristano, Sardegna, Italia"},"fr":{"about 1128–":"environ 1128–Décédée","1124–Male":"1124–Décédé","1150–1204":"1150–1204","1128–Female":"1128–Décédée","1128":"1128","1204":"1204","1124":"1124","about 1128":"environ 1128","1150":"1150","Laconi,Oristano,Sardinia,Italy.":"Laconi, Oristano, Sardegna, Italie","Arborea, Oristan, Sardegna, Italy":"Arborea, Oristano, Sardegna, Italie","lifeSummary":"Pelegrina di Arborea est née environ 1128, à Arborea, Oristano, Sardegna, Italie. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Barison I de Lacon Serra."},"de":{"about 1128–":"um 1128–Verstorben","1124–Male":"1124–Verstorben","1150–1204":"1150–1204","1128–Female":"1128–Verstorben","1128":"1128","1204":"1204","1124":"1124","about 1128":"um 1128","1150":"1150","Laconi,Oristano,Sardinia,Italy.":"Laconi, Oristano, Sardinien, It